item.content:encoded:
We Are Open!

We are back to our normal hours and operations! Thank you to our clients during this time of adjustment. We are so appreciative of your continued understanding and support, and we are looking forward to seeing you all soon!

[foogallery id="257"]  

The Tail Wag Inn boarding kennel is a locally owned business, dedicated to providing the highest standard of love and care to your fur-babies when you’re out of town, working, or otherwise. Our staff is comprised of animal lovers that take great pride in their abilities to keep your pets happy, healthy, and safe. Take a look through our website to learn a little bit more about our facility and what sets us apart from others! Please also feel free to give us a call with any questions, or stop by for a tour any time during business hours (no appointment needed!).

item.title: Frequently Asked Questions
item.dc:creator: plsa7000@hotmail.com
item.content:encoded:
Please take some time to look over the following frequently asked questions below. Feel free to give us a call at 503-554-9000 for any clarification, or for any other questions that you may have! [foogallery id="222"]

Boarding questions:

[learn_more caption="What is required to board my pet?"] For dogs: rabies vaccine, DHPP vaccine, and a bordetella vaccine. For cats: rabies vaccine, FVRCP vaccine, and a Feline Leukemia vaccine.[/learn_more] [learn_more caption="What if my vet doesn’t recommend that my pet receives one of the required vaccines?"] We will accept your pet with whatever vaccines your vet deems safe and recommended for your pet. If your pet cannot receive a specific vaccine that we require, please have your vet fax over a doctor’s note stating that they do not vaccinate said pet against whichever required vaccines stated above, and we will keep this information on file for any future stays.[/learn_more] [learn_more caption="Do you have breed restrictions?"] No, we do not! We accept breeds of all ages, temperaments, and sizes! We also board birds, rodents, rabbits, reptiles, turtles, pigs, etc. Please call for details![/learn_more] [learn_more caption="What is included in the standard boarding price?"] Standard boarding includes, for dogs, an individualized, indoor/outdoor kennel. We provide food and bedding if you would prefer to use ours instead of bringing your pets’ food. If your dog is compatible with other dogs, we are often able to find “kennel mates” for him/her to play with throughout the duration of their stay. Please see the “What are kennel mates?” question for more information. We are in and out of each dogs’ kennel throughout the day giving attention and care, though if you are looking to add a specific activity for your dog, an additional charge of $9.00 per activity, per session will apply. Please see out services and rates page for additional information. For cats, a minimum of two “kitty condos” are assigned. Depending on availability, each cat can receive two to five kitty condos to meander through. We provide food and bedding if you would prefer to use ours (as opposed to bringing your pets’ food). Please see our facility pictures (located on our home page) to get a better idea of what the kitty condos look like. We also offer two different cat activities, with the additional charge of $9.00 per activity, per session. Please see our rates page for additional information.[/learn_more] [learn_more caption="How big are the kennels?"] Large Dog Kennel: 20’x 4’ outside, 5’x 4’ inside Medium Dog Kennel: 20’x 3.5’ outside, 5’x 3.5’ inside Small Dog Kennel: 12’x 2.5’ outside, 5’ x 2.5 inside Kitty Condo: 2’ x 2.5’ per condo[/learn_more] [learn_more caption="What does your facility look like?"] Please return to our home page and click through the gallery of photos there to see pictures of the inside of the dog kennel, outside of the kennels, cat room, play yard, and more![/learn_more] [learn_more caption="Can I come in for a tour?"] Yes! We do tours everyday during business hours, no appointment needed! The best time to stop in to take a look around would be between 9-5 to avoid all of our heavy cleaning and feeding times![/learn_more] [learn_more caption="Can I bring my dog on the tour?"] No, we do not allow dogs to come along on the tour due to insurance liability issues![/learn_more] [learn_more caption="What food do you provide?"] We serve both Diamond brand Maintenance and Diamond brand Lamb and Rice for dogs. For cats, we serve Maintenance Diamond Brand. We do have canned wet dog food and canned wet cat food, if needed to entice eating. We also have Milkbone brand dog treats (and sometimes, various other treats!) that are given sparingly throughout your dogs’ stay with us. Please notify us if your dog has any allergies so that we can make sure to stick to their strict diet only![/learn_more] [learn_more caption="Can I bring my pets’ own food/treats?"] Yes, of course. We highly recommend bringing your pets’ own food to avoid any digestive upset. There is no additional charge to use our food or your own food. Please bring your pets’ food however you would like (in a tupperware, ziplock bag, original bag, pre-baggied, etc.) and we can accommodate accordingly. We have standard measuring cups as a basis for feeding amounts, though you can bring your own “scoop” (cup, mug, container, etc.) and we’d be happy to use that instead. We are able to refrigerate/freeze food as well, if needed.[/learn_more] [learn_more caption="Can I bring my pets’ blanket/bed/toys?"] Yes, you are more than welcome to bring bedding and toys. Again, we do have blankets here that we will provide if you choose not to bring anything. We just ask that whatever you bring is machine washable in case of any accidents. Also, please keep in mind that even though your pet may not normally tear or shred their bedding or belongings at home, dogs may be more prone to doing so here, so we ask that you do not bring any very special or irreplaceable items for your pets’ stay. For elderly pets, please make sure to bring any special mats/beds to keep them comfortable! We have a limited number of beds available and bringing your own will ensure that he/she always has one within his/her kennel. In regards to toys, please only bring toys that you are comfortable leaving your pet unattended with. Although we are here throughout the day, we are not here to monitor pets and their toy habits over night.[/learn_more] [learn_more caption="What are kennel mates?"] We like to try to find a suitable friend for your dog to board with who is the same size, age, and temperament! Most dogs enjoy getting to have a friend to board with, and this is a great way for dogs to expend some of their energy without adding on additional activities! We never put non-compatible dogs in with other dogs and we never leave compatible dogs that do not seem to be getting along in the same run together. We always make sure that both dogs are content with the friend that we have matched them with and we are continuously checking up on them throughout their stay to ensure that they are boarding and playing well together! As far as feeding goes, we never feed dogs from different families together, and always make sure to completely separate both dogs before putting food bowls or treats down. Once they are finished eating, we completely remove empty bowls before reintroducing kennel mates! Lastly, we never board un-neutered males with un-spayed females. There is no additional charge for kennel mates. Most owners prefer this for the socialization aspect of their dog and the dogs generally enjoy having a friend to play with throughout the day! Please call with anymore questions in regards to kennel mates.[/learn_more] [learn_more caption="How much does it cost for my dog to get a bath?"] We base our bathing prices off of the dirtiness, difficulty, and hairiness of a dog along with the total time it takes us to complete the full bath, nails, and ears package. Our base price for the smallest sized dog is $25.00. Again, with each scheduled bath, a nail trim and ear cleaning is included, though if you’d prefer us not to do these, please let us know and we can skip either/both. Please call and ask for a quote! We are able to give your dog a bath while they board with us, or with a scheduled appointment for specifically just the bath. Please call ahead to set up an appointment, if needed. PLEASE NOTE: while boarding, if you choose to sign your pet up for a bath, the bath will be scheduled as close to your predetermined pick up date and time as possible. If you are picking up your pet before noon-two, we will schedule the bath to be done the evening before. We will give a morning “clean up bath” if needed to ensure that your pet goes home clean![/learn_more] [learn_more caption="Can I pick up my pet after 7:30pm or drop off my pet prior to 7:30am?"] We do have a before/after hours fee of $25.00 per ½ hour, up to one hour only (no earlier than 6:30am and no later than 8:30pm). To clarify, we do not do this unless the drop off or pick up has been scheduled prior to the day of and we are not always able to accommodate these situations. We cannot guarantee that we will have the ability to come early or stay late with same day notice, so if you are interested in this, please call for more information! [/learn_more] [learn_more caption="How often should I get my dog bathed?"] According to the ASPCA, they recommend bathing your dog at least once every three months, though some some dogs may require more frequent baths if they spend a lot of time outdoors or if they have skin problems. Please see their web page on grooming tips here: https://www.aspca.org/pet-care/dog-care/dog-grooming-tips[/learn_more] [learn_more caption="Can I bring my own shampoo?"] Yes, we can use specific shampoo that you bring in! Otherwise, we will use the dog shampoo that we have on hand at the time (TropiClean, Nootie, Earthbath, etc.) that seems like the best fit for your pets’ needs (i.e. oatmeal, anti-itch, hypo, or normal).[/learn_more] [learn_more caption="What is the protocol/procedure for if my pet is injured or becomes ill?"] After accessing the situation, we will try to reach you first, and then your emergency contact(s), for further instructions/information. If we are unable to make contact, we will call your veterinarian to decide if your pet requires treatment. If your veterinarian clinic is closed, we will take your pet to the Family Pet Clinic of Newberg or an emergency clinic.[/learn_more] [learn_more caption="What forms of payment are accepted?"] We accept cash, checks, debit cards, Visa, MasterCard, Discover, and American Express cards. Payment is typically made at the time of pet pickup.[/learn_more] [learn_more caption="Do I need to sign a contract when I board my pet?"] Yes! Each time your pet comes to stay, you will be asked to sign the contract. Please feel free to download a copy if you’d like to look it over (located on our reservations and contact page). We will print one at the time of drop off![/learn_more] [learn_more caption="How do you charge for boarding?"] All pet guests will be charged for the arrival day of boarding, regardless of drop off time. If your pet is picked up by 12 noon on the day of departure, you will not be charged for that days boarding. Any time after noon is another full days charge. No half day charges or daycare packages can be added on to avoid being charged for another full day after noon. Disclaimer: Prices are subject to change without notice[/learn_more] [learn_more caption="What is a play yard activity and how do you group dogs together for this activity?"] A play yard activity is a loosely supervised, 30 minute minimum play time with dogs who are also listed as “compatible” in our system. Only dogs whose owners have signed their pup up for the play yard activity will go out to play. We work hard to match up dogs of the same size, age, temperament, and play style based off of owner information and prior boarding experiences here. We introduce dogs (on leash) in the play yard and determine whether or not they will get along and play well together. Once we have deemed them as a good match (or group), we periodically check back in on said group over the course of the duration of the play yard. Though the activity is a minimum of 30 minutes, we typically let groups play for as long as possible based off of weather and the number of groups set up to go out and play. We never put non-compatible dogs in the play yard. We never put un-spayed and un-neutered dogs out together. We never leave groups out that we aren’t confident are getting along. That being said, animals are unpredictable, though we do our best to ensure a safe and enjoyable environment for your dog![/learn_more] [learn_more caption="Can you give my pet their medication or injections?"] Yes, we can! Please make sure to leave us with detailed instructions on how much, how often, and how you would like us to administer them! We use small pieces of cheese, peanut butter, or little bits of wet food for pills, though you are welcome to bring pill pockets or anything else you may typically use![/learn_more] [learn_more caption="Can my pet wear their collar while boarding?"] Due to the risk of collars/harnesses catching on the fencing, we do not allow pets to wear their collars or harnesses while boarding. We provide a tear away collar with their name and our information on it for your pet to wear. If necessary, we can use their own harness/collar during walks, though while within the kennel, they will not be wearing anything other than the tear away collar.[/learn_more] [learn_more caption="What is a Pet Care Technician?"] Upon hire, all employees are referred to as pet care techs. However, we have three tests consisting of Tail Wag Inn specific information ranging from short answer to multiple choice questions. After an employee’s first three months hits, they are asked to take the level one pet care test. After passing said test, they are now considered a level one pet tech. The same goes for an employee at six months for the level two and a test at one year for the level three tech.[/learn_more] [learn_more caption="How does the kennel stay warm in the winter?"] Our floors are heated, so that, combined with the fact that most of the building is constructed of concrete, results in us having the ability to keep the heat trapped within the kennel! You are also more than welcome to bring in sweaters and blankets from home if you think this will help your dog to keep toasty warm! We do not, however, have the ability to plug in any heating pads or heated beds.[/learn_more] [learn_more caption="How does the kennel stay cool in the summer?"] As stated above, we do have a mostly concrete kennel building, which is good at maintaining the coolness when needed or warmth when needed! We have six high velocity fans rotating on the ceiling/roof early in the morning and late at night to pull cool air into the building and we work to keep the cool air contained in the building throughout the hot, summer days! You are also more than welcome to bring in cooling mats, cooling coats, etc. to help keep you dog cool if you’d like! Generally speaking, our kennel building stays between 10-20 degrees cooler than outside during the summer, rarely reaching temps higher than 80 degrees![/learn_more] [learn_more caption="What do I do if my dog has loud noise anxiety (fireworks, gun shots, thunder, etc.)?"] If your dog reacts to loud noises such as those listed above, please consult with your vet to see if they’re able to prescribe “as needed” anti-anxiety meds or sedation meds. We do try to cancel out these types of noises as much as possible using our radio and fans, though we generally have more success with prescribed medication to help your dog to keep calm in these situations. We do have a gun range neighboring us (about 0.2 miles down the road, across the street) and the noise does carry over to us (though not on a very regular basis).[/learn_more] [learn_more caption="What should I expect after boarding my dog?"] After boarding your dog, you may notice him or her to be more tired than normal. Remember, your dog needs to rest from his vacation just like you! Although dogs have unlimited access to water while here, a small percentage may drink and eat more upon returning home. They may also display mild digestive upsets. It is Tail Wag Inn’s highest priority to provide unparalleled care and attention for your dog. We want every experience you have with us to be exceptional and we strive to give you the best service anywhere. Our expert staff and modern facility offer the best of everything your dog needs to be safe, comfortable, and happy. Your dog is a member of your family and will be treated as one of ours. Please look over this what to expect after boarding sheet for more information![/learn_more] [learn_more caption="Is there anything I should do to prepare my pet for their first boarding experience?"] If you are worried about how your dog may do during their first overnight stay with us, we recommend setting up a daycare appointment in advance so that we can give you more information on how they respond to the kennel setting throughout the day! This also helps with dogs with separation anxiety to give them comfort in knowing that you’ll be back to pick them up![/learn_more] [learn_more caption="Do I have to bring my dog in for a temperament test prior to their first stay?"] No, we do not require any “testing” prior to dropping off! All of our kennels are individualized and we don’t do any off leash introductions between dogs who have never met before, so no prior screening is necessary![/learn_more] [learn_more caption="How long does the check in process take and what should I expect?"] The check in process typically takes about five to ten minutes for new clients and for returning, roughly one to five minutes! We go through verifying any added services that you may want to add (bathing, nail trim, activities, potty walks, etc.), review vet info, phone numbers, email addresses, feeding/medication instructions, and printing/signing the contract. We ask that you leave you pet in your vehicle until the check in process is complete, please![/learn_more] [learn_more caption="What is kennel cough?"] Canine cough is a highly contagious respiratory disease that is much like the human cold, and generally does not require medical care. Dogs catch kennel cough by inhaling the bacteria or virus particles into their respiratory tract. Vets will often prescribe cough suppressants to reduce throat irritation and/or antibiotics to help the pet recover quickly, but it will usually resolve itself on its own. We want all of our clients to be aware and to feel comfortable asking us any questions! We aren't medically trained professionals, so we recommend talking to your vet if you are exceptionally worried. The bordetella vaccine is much like the flu shot for humans in the sense that even if your dog is vaccinated, they can still contract kennel cough. Please see this canine cough fact sheet for more information. [/learn_more]

item.title: Meet Our Staff
item.dc:creator: plsa7000@hotmail.com
item.content:encoded: Tail Wag-Inn has been owned and operated by Allison Best since 1997 and has been established as one of the premier boarding kennel facilities in the Yamhill County. Conveniently located in Dundee, Oregon, (in the heart of Oregon Wine Country) we offer overnight boarding, full daycare, ½ day care, bathing, nail trims and extra special activities during your pets' stay! We have pet owners from all over the area, including those who come from Marion, Yamhill, Multnomah, Polk, Clackamas, Washington, and Tillamook counties, among others! They love our facility and our convenient location on 99W, just south of Newberg. Visit our services and rates page for a complete list of our services and rates. Each of our Pet Care Technicians (pictured below) have been certified and are trained to monitor your pet during its stay. We care about your pet's health, happiness, and well-being. item.title: Reservations and Contact
item.dc:creator: plsa7000@hotmail.com
item.content:encoded:
Making a reservation is easy! Click the link below to access our customer portal and make reservations online, or give us a call at 503-554-9000

We will have you sign a contract when you arrive. If you would like to download a copy prior to your arrival, please do.

Why should you make a reservation with Tail Wag-Inn?

Our quality care and beautiful park-like setting says it all! We have pet owners from Tigard, Tualatin, Sherwood, Newberg and McMinnville who love our facility and our convenient location on 99W, just south of Newberg. We also have pet owners from Portland, Lake Oswego, Willsonville, West Linn and Oregon City as well, choosing our facility over those that offer only small, not park-like, cement holding cells.

Reservations Reminders:

Make your reservations early, as we book quickly during the holidays and summer months. Let us know the date you intend to drop off your pet and the date you intend to pick them up. Please provide phone numbers, email addresses, and contact names where someone can be reached in case of emergency, or if we simply have a question. Be sure to let us know of any needs or special problems your pets may have such as; hearing loss, fear of thunder, fireworks, or gunshots, excessive barking, allergies, or aggression problems, etc. This ensures we are able to provide the best care possible!

Customer Portal:

Please use this link to access your customer portal. Current customers that have not set up their customer portal can do so by selecting "Are you a current customer?", and entering the email address or phone number we have on file. New customers should select "Are you a new customer?", and create their client file. Please email (happydogs@tailwaginn.com) or call (503-554-9000), if you have any difficulties.
If you are interested in becoming a part of the Tail Wag Inn team, please fill out our online employment application! If you have any questions, please give our office a call at 503-554-9000 or visit us in Dundee, Oregon. We are located at milepost 27 on Highway 99W about one half mile south of Dundee, just past the entrance to the new bypass. Directions: 20999 Hwy 99W, Dundee, OR, 97115 [foogallery id="298"]

item.title: Our Facility
item.dc:creator: plsa7000@hotmail.com
item.content:encoded: [foogallery id="433"]     Both owner and staff here at Tail Wag Inn know that an indoor/outdoor environment while boarding is ideal for your dog. It’s more natural than a smaller, indoor-only facility with stressful, high noise levels, and artificial exercise areas. We’re very proud of our state-of-the-art facility with an average of 96 square feet per run, allowing your dog more than ample space to choose their own, comfortable environment, whether it be inside or out.  The interior of the building has heated floors for the wintertime and is well ventilated for the warmer weather. We offer a wide variety of one-on-one activities, many of which are outdoors, where most active dogs prefer to be, in a beautiful, serene country setting. The outside runs are fully covered, to protect your fur-children from harsh sun-rays, and more frequently - Oregon rain.  Our cattery is completely indoors, in our fully temperature controlled office building. Your kitty will occupy a series of what we call “Kitty Condos”, which are gated cubes with openings in between, to allow them access to more space. We provide litter boxes, litter, stainless steel bowls, hiding boxes, and blankets to make sure your cat stays clean, healthy, and comfortable. Our cattery has multiple cat trees and a window ledge that your cat will have the opportunity to explore. Cats are only let out individually. The kitties are frequently checked on, loved and pet, and visited by our staff throughout the day. We offer activities that you can sign your cat up for, which would give them guaranteed one-on-one attention and love from a staff member. Visit our services and rates page for a complete list! Conveniently located in Dundee, Oregon, (in the heart of Oregon Wine Country) we offer overnight boarding, full daycare, ½ day care, bathing, nail trims and extra special activities during your pets' stay! We have pet owners from all over the area, including those who come from Marion, Yamhill, Multnomah, Polk, Clackamas, Washington, and Tillamook counties, among others!
